{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507903"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:59:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:59:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2690"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2690"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.77,0.07,0.01,0.08,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2690"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78876"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2690"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2690"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64225"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1131"},{"type":"tags","id":"1132"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"6155"},{"type":"tags","id":"6281"},{"type":"tags","id":"6351"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3266"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3267"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3312"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27028"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78876"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 62-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a painful right knee. The pain is such that he cannot weight bear and can only limp. The previous day he had slipped and fallen onto his right knee whilst out jogging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, there is obvious swelling and bruising of the right knee, with tenderness over the anterior aspect. Active flexion is painful and limited to 40\u00b0. No further examination is feasible due to the pain. His vital signs are within normal range.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Plain X-ray","Ultrasound","Bone scan","MRI scan","Joint aspiration"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESimilar to other lower limb joints, the need for an \u003Cstrong\u003EX-ray\u003C/strong\u003E post-injury can be directed by the Ottawa knee rules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Ottawa knee rules suggest a knee X-ray is indicated after an acute knee injury plus one of:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAge over 55 years\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETenderness at the head of the fibula\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIsolated tenderness of the patella\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInability to flex the knee to 90 degrees\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInability to bear weight (unable to take four steps)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf these are all negative, an MRI or ultrasound is indicated. However, from the stem, he is 62 years old (over 55), is unable to flex the knee to 90 degrees, and is having issues mobilising. Therefore, a knee \u003Cstrong\u003EX-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf this is normal and suggests no fracture, consideration should turn towards meniscal or soft tissue injury, and hence \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI\u003C/strong\u003E imaging performed. This is the imaging modality of choice as it provides the best imaging of soft tissues such as the ligaments and menisci and can be relied on to rule out injuries of these structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf an isolated tendon injury is suspected, an \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful. It can also help to identify a joint effusion but is limited in what it can see in obese or muscular patients and cannot be relied on to rule out meniscal or soft tissue injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebone scan\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as first-line imaging in acute knee injury. It is typically used for detecting bone metastases, stress fractures, or infections, but not for acute trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJoint aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated in the case that septic arthritis may be suspected. The recent fall, which may have caused an open wound and entrance for bacteria, is of concern from this history. However, there are no other signs of septic arthritis such as fever, being systemically unwell, erythema, and warmth over the knee joint. Hence, it is not indicated in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["X-ray is indicated in acute knee injury in accordance to the Ottawa knee rules.","All patients aged over 55 years with acute knee injury require a knee X-ray."],"references":["Yao K, Haque T. The Ottawa knee rules - a useful clinical decision tool. Aust Fam Physician. 2012 Apr;41(4):223-4. PMID: 22472684. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22472684/","Ridley U, Ridley L, 2020. Imaging of the knee: Common acute presentations to general practice. Australian Journal of General Practice: RACGP. Vol 49, Issue 6. DOI: 10.31128/AJGP-10-19-5120. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/june/knee-imaging","Hirvasniemi J, Runhaar J, van der Heijden RA, Zokaeinikoo M, Yang M, Li X, Tan J, Rajamohan HR, Zhou Y, Deniz CM, Caliva F, Iriondo C, Lee JJ, Liu F, Martinez AM, Namiri N, Pedoia V, Panfilov E, Bayramoglu N, Nguyen HH, Nieminen MT, Saarakkala S, Tiulpin A, Lin E, Li A, Li V, Dam EB, Chaudhari AS, Kijowski R, Bierma-Zeinstra S, Oei EHG, Klein S. The KNee OsteoArthritis Prediction (KNOAP2020) challenge: An image analysis challenge to predict incident symptomatic radiographic knee osteoarthritis from MRI and X-ray images. Osteoarthritis Cartilage. 2023 Jan;31(1):115-125. doi: 10.1016/j.joca.2022.10.001. Epub 2022 Oct 12. PMID: 36243308; PMCID: PMC10323696. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36243308/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64225"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2690"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16882"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16882"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/92c47d42-cc89-433d-b425-0de143ad46ed.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/92c47d42-cc89-433d-b425-0de143ad46ed.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":561,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64225","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64225"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T10:11:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T10:12:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2690"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78876"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{